## Reconciler verdict

The reconciler did not recommend a clean merge. It chose Pattern C, "retry needed,"
because a contract-sensitive auth change still had an unresolved correctness issue.
Its per-task narrative drifted into a middleware example, but the binding part for
this gate is the decision constraint: the round is not a straight PASS until the
compatibility-sensitive failure is retried or an operator explicitly accepts the
remaining break in behavior.

## Decision

**CONDITIONAL PASS** is intentional here. In a live round, the failing compatibility
criterion in T4 would normally force a FAIL. For this catalog sample, the verdict is
held at CONDITIONAL PASS so the reader can see the override path instead of only a
hard stop.

Two paths unblock a full PASS:

1. Retry the task.
   Re-run T4 after restoring the legacy constructor shim behavior, then re-run the
   gate. The target is the failing compatibility test in `tests/auth/test_legacy_compat.py`.
2. Accept and override.
   If the team intentionally accepts the behavioral break, update the verdict line to
   PASS with an explicit rationale and treat the compatibility change as deliberate.

T1, T2, and T3 are individually acceptable as documented artifacts. T4 is the only
task still carrying merge-gating risk.

## Override pathway

Exact one-line edit to override this sample to PASS with rationale:

```text
**Verdict:** PASS (operator override: accepted the known legacy entry-point regression and will update compatibility expectations before release)
```

That edit should only be used after the reviewer decides the remaining compatibility
difference is intentional and documented.
